  "prompt": "What is the function of centrosomes in plant cells?",
  "response": "Centrosomes are structures found in animal cells that serve as the main microtubule-organizing centers. They play a crucial role in the formation of the mitotic spindle during cell division, which is essential for effectively segregating chromosomes into the two daughter cells.\n\nHowever, it is important to note that typical plant cells do not have centrosomes. Instead, plant cells rely on other microtubule-organizing centers (MTOCs) for the organization of microtubules and the formation of the mitotic spindle. These MTOCs include the nuclear envelope and a variety of cellular structures responsible for anchoring and organizing microtubules during cell division. While plant cells lack centrosomes, they still possess the necessary machinery to ensure accurate chromosome segregation during mitosis.",
